Good. That’s the natural next move.

If we generalize from triangle → circle → square to regular n-gon → circle → square, the structure becomes much clearer, and you can watch the boundary ratios flow toward the circle as n increases.

Equal-area transform chain

Let a regular n-gon have side length a.

1) Regular n-gon

Area:
A_n=\frac{n a^2}{4\tan(\pi/n)}

Perimeter:
P_n=na

2) Equal-area circle

Let the circle have radius r_n, with the same area:
\pi r_n^2=A_n

So:
r_n=\sqrt{\frac{A_n}{\pi}}

Circumference:
C_n=2\pi r_n=2\sqrt{\pi A_n}

Substitute A_n:
C_n=2\sqrt{\pi\cdot \frac{n a^2}{4\tan(\pi/n)}}

C_n=a\sqrt{\frac{\pi n}{\tan(\pi/n)}}

3) Equal-area square

Let square side be s_n, same area:
s_n=\sqrt{A_n}

Perimeter:
P_{\square,n}=4\sqrt{A_n}

Substitute:
P_{\square,n}=4\sqrt{\frac{n a^2}{4\tan(\pi/n)}}

P_{\square,n}=2a\sqrt{\frac{n}{\tan(\pi/n)}}

⸻

The three key ratios

These are the real heart of the transform.

Polygon → Circle

R_{PC}(n)=\frac{C_n}{P_n}

Substitute:
R_{PC}(n)=\frac{a\sqrt{\frac{\pi n}{\tan(\pi/n)}}}{na}

R_{PC}(n)=\sqrt{\frac{\pi}{n\tan(\pi/n)}}

⸻

Circle → Square

R_{CS}(n)=\frac{P_{\square,n}}{C_n}

Substitute:
R_{CS}(n)=\frac{2a\sqrt{\frac{n}{\tan(\pi/n)}}}{a\sqrt{\frac{\pi n}{\tan(\pi/n)}}}

Everything except \pi cancels:

R_{CS}(n)=\frac{2}{\sqrt{\pi}}

That is beautiful, because it is independent of n.

So for any equal-area regular polygon → circle → square chain,

\boxed{ \frac{P_{\square}}{C}=\frac{2}{\sqrt{\pi}} }

and therefore

\boxed{ \pi=\left(\frac{2}{R_{CS}}\right)^2 }

That is the invariant you were sniffing out.

⸻

Polygon → Square

R_{PS}(n)=\frac{P_{\square,n}}{P_n}

Substitute:
R_{PS}(n)=\frac{2a\sqrt{\frac{n}{\tan(\pi/n)}}}{na}

R_{PS}(n)=2\sqrt{\frac{1}{n\tan(\pi/n)}}

⸻

What happens as n \to \infty

As the regular polygon approaches a circle:

\tan(\pi/n)\sim \pi/n

So:
n\tan(\pi/n)\to \pi

Then the ratios become:

Polygon → Circle

R_{PC}(n)=\sqrt{\frac{\pi}{n\tan(\pi/n)}}\to 1

Makes sense: the polygon perimeter approaches the circle circumference.

Polygon → Square

R_{PS}(n)=2\sqrt{\frac{1}{n\tan(\pi/n)}}\to \frac{2}{\sqrt{\pi}}

Same constant emerges.

Circle → Square

R_{CS}(n)=\frac{2}{\sqrt{\pi}}

Already constant for all n.

⸻

Why this is interesting

This means the circle→square boundary ratio under equal area is universal.

It does not matter whether you begin with:
	•	triangle
	•	pentagon
	•	hexagon
	•	100-gon

Once you go through the equal-area circle and compare to the equal-area square, the same constant appears:

\frac{P_{\square}}{C}=\frac{2}{\sqrt{\pi}}

So the circle is functioning like a boundary normalization lens.

Another clean form

Since
C=2\sqrt{\pi A}
\qquad\text{and}\qquad
P_{\square}=4\sqrt{A}

then
\frac{P_{\square}}{C}
=
\frac{4\sqrt{A}}{2\sqrt{\pi A}}
=
\frac{2}{\sqrt{\pi}}

The area cancels too.

So this invariant is really about:
	•	same area
	•	circle boundary law
	•	square boundary law

not about the starting polygon specifically.

The starting polygon only tells you how far away you are from the circle before normalization.

