The most interesting next step

The next elegant thing to do would be to define a shape efficiency function:

E(\text{shape})=\frac{2\sqrt{\pi A}}{P}

This equals:
	•	1 for a circle
	•	less than 1 for every other shape

For a regular n-gon:
E_n=\sqrt{\frac{\pi}{n\tan(\pi/n)}}

which is exactly your polygon→circle ratio.

So your intuition can be sharpened into:

track perimeter under fixed area, and the circle reveals itself as the unique normalized optimum, with \pi as the governing constant.

